<DOC><DOCNO> AP900717-0031 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-90 0449EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-17 0388</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0399</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Dips, Stocks Up</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar slipped against the Japanese yen inTokyo today, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange firmedon arbitrage buying.   The dollar closed at 148.20 yen, down 0.23 yen from Monday'sclose of 148.43 yen. It opened at 147.87 yen and ranged between147.80 yen and 148.30 yen.   Spot transactions totaled $8.568 billion, up from $7.959 billionon Monday.   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 150.55points, or 0.46 percent, to 33,172.28. The index surged 377.36points on Monday.   Volume on the first section was estimated at 600 million shares,up from Monday's 580 million shares.   In bond dealings, the price of the benchmark No. 119 10-yearJapanese government bond stood at 86.87 points as of 5 p.m., downfrom Monday's close of 87.06 points. The yield was 7.225 percent,up from 7.185 percent.   Currency dealers said movement of the dollar was narrow beforethe release in Washington of U.S. trade data later in the day.   ``Dealers' sentiment here generally favors the dollar to slipfurther'' because of Friday's cut in the U.S. key federal fundsrate, among other factors, said Akihiko Kagawa, a dealer with Bankof Tokyo.   On the stock market, traders said share prices moved higher onarbitrage buying in the day's closing minutes of trade.   Yoshiro Inoue of Nomura Securities said share prices openedfirm, aided by a steep overnight advance on Wall Street, andtransactions were brisk in early trading before a rumor hit themarket that Japan's central bank would raise its key rate for loansto commercial banks near in the future.   Japan's discount rate now stands at 5.25 percent, one of thelowest among industrialized nations. The country has been underpressure from its trading partners to raise the rate to stem theyen's weakness against the dollar and other major currencies.   Higher interest rates tend to make a currency more attractive toinvestors on the one hand, but make security investment lessattractive on the other hand.   In the last few minutes of the day's trading the benchmarkNikkei index shot up on buying linked to stock-index arbitrage,Inoue said. In the arbitrage, traders bought shares coupled to ashort sale of the same securities to profit from a disparity ofprices, he said.</TEXT></DOC>